Great class, but no direction. Learn more grammar than ever before.

Tina is one of the best professors I have had at Columbia. She has an excellent command of the material. Her lectures are interesting and organized, along with slides & reading material.  She works hard to help her students do well in the class.  Her thoughtful comments on assigned papers are extraordinarily helpful.  I highly recommend Tina!

Tina is one of the best professors I have had at Columbia.  She has great command of the material and she works tirelessly to help her students do well.  Her comments on assignments are thorough, thoughtful and very helpful. I looked forward to her lectures.  She is an outstanding instructor and I would love to take another class with her.

Tina is an awesome professor. She is very knowledgeable and articulate, her lectures are  engaging, and she is very supportive in helping her students perform well. The clarity with which Tina delivers the course material is brilliant, and she helps you frame and articulate your arguments really well. I strongly recommend her class.

Tina Rivers is the best teacher I've had at Columbia  and one of the best teachers I've ever had, period. She's an incredibly knowledgeable, no-nonsense instructor. A spectacular professor!  She gave the most concise and brilliant explanation on how to write a compelling essay (any type of essay)I've ever heard.   She is a total rock-star professor who thinks clearly and is delightfully organized.  Can't recomend her classes enough!
Fantastic teacher!!!
Tina is a phenomenal professor. I came into her class confused by and disinterested in art history and left looking to take another art class. I learned so much with her.

Tina is the perfect TA to have if you are taking this class as a requirement. Not only is she super hot and extremely articulate, she can tell you where to listen to the best house music in the city. Great TA, easy to understand and very good at explaining difficult topics. Fair grader and easily approached. Highly recommended.
you'd be a fool not to take her class.  she is super smart, generous with her time, and makes art history fun, as cheesy as that sounds.  the best.
The best Professor I've had, regardless of subject!  Professor Blaer taught Physics that even a layman can understand.  Very rare teacher in today's world.
Alan is a legent and by far the best teacher I ever had. I took 2 courses in Electromagnetism with him in 1982-83 and I still remember and use his lecture....
The best the school has to offer.
THE BEST I CLASS I EVER TOOK

Professor Blaer is one of the best teachers I have ever had.  His lectures are incredibly clear and he is tremendously helpful both as a lecturer and at his office hours. 2 words: THE BEST!!! Not only is he an excellent teacher, he's SUUUUUUUUPPPPPEEEEEEEERRRRRRRRRR nice, and he looks so adorable..u just wanna pinch his cheeks!

One of the warmest, cleverest, clearest, and most helpful people anybody is likely to meet.
ABSOLUTELY THE BEST!!!!!!!
He is the man.

Class and workload is difficult and with a weekend class, its at a fast pace. His tests are all about understanding the concepts and not memorizing, so it makes you learn

Not an easy class and he will push you to think logically. Exams are pretty tough but manageable. I enjoyed his lectures alot even though he tends to over explain but it helps to understand the topics. He is very open so you can stop by his lab on the Saturdays and he will make time for you to go over exams or answer questions

One of the only professors that doesn't just read the slides and makes you understand concepts. Very down to earth and very responsive when you email him. Nice enough, clear, and fair. My only real complaint about Professar Jethwani is that although her lectures had generally interesting subject matter, they were extremely dry which made engaging difficult.

she is an amazing professor and is very passionate about her work. you will learn so much from her. i couldn't recommend her more.

she's so beautiful, cool and a total brainiac as well. she teaches one of the best classes i've ever taken.

comment: I found Kirsti to be an excellent Capstone advisor: she is critical, but her criticism is constructive, specific and never arbitrary. Unlike many professors, she took the time to review our work product and give us helpful feedback as well as help us decide on a clear strategy for the research and analysis portion of the work.

Kirsti provided valuable guidance as an advisor to our team. I was disappointed that I didn't get the grade I wanted as I put in a lot of work. That aside, she was very thoughtful in handling the team, taking the time for healthy team dynamics and getting to know us. She skillfully balanced being an expert and giving us control of the project.
The professor supported us in writing a great capstone project that was published. Hard work. long hours.

Capstones are intensive,but Dr. Samuels made the project manageable. She has a wealth of knowledge and practical experience that she was willing and open to sharing. She took time to learn each of her students. She played up our strengths and assisted us in navigating through our challenges. Great teacher; Seasoned professional; Highly recommended.
Kirsti seemed disengaged and unavailable and provided little to no guidance to the team during the project. While she has an interesting CV, I did not feel like I learnt anything from her.

Kirsti was a great instructor. Her feedback on work was thoughtful and grounded in her wealth of experience in both peacebuilding and leadership development. She knew each student well, and was conscious of our group dynamics. (Note the bad reviews come from folks who declined to provide their grade. You get out what you put in.)

Kirsti is a wonderful professor and leader. She is very intentional, giving strategic guidance when needed, but also giving teams space to figure things out. Our team had an emergency abroad, and Kirsti went above and beyond to give us the tools to deal with the situation, provide support & show compassion. I would recommend her class to everyone.

Kirsti is a seasoned peace-building professional. She is knowledgeable of the theory and the practicalities of the field, which makes her a great tutor for a graduate course. I can only imagine that a course with her would be not only interesting but intellectually challenging.

Not a subject matter expert. Does not answer any questions. All feedback on the papers is about grammar. Don't take the class! comment: Professor Betts makes you work for it, but he's absolutely brilliant and very respected by his students and the faculty. There aren't that many recent reviews for Professor Martha Kim, so I wanted to add one here. To put things straight -- she's a very good professor when it comes to lecturing. The second portion of the semester might be difficult, but you do learn a lot. The workload for the class is very fair.

For how difficult the subject is, Martha makes the material very understandable. Her lectures are amazing and help a lot with projects. Course is 4 projects with no midterms or finals, projects are challenging but very doable, even if you don't go to class commonly. Also completely unrelated but hands down the hottest professor at Columbia.

Jointly taught class; she taught MIPS assembly part. Assignments are tough, and tests even tougher, if you do not understand the material. Some people don't go to class at all, bored by lectures andor course material, but then they struggle very hard on their own. Midterm grades may be low, and likely so are final grades. Difficult class overall.

Awful teacher, she expects you to know everything she does and her lectures teach you nothing. No one stays awake in class if they actually go. She makes tests way harder than anything you've seen in homeworks or in the book. The average on our midterm was just above 50. Do not take a class with this professor if you can avoid it.

I think I'm most struck by, and appreciative of, Dr. Blair's thoughtfulness as a coach. I think anyone working with her can anticipate receiving attention that reflects your experience, your needs, her experience, and her desire to see you thrive. This does not mean she is always easy, but will both push and protect you as needed.
Madelyn is very aligned with the learning objectives of our course. Her mentoring and coaching were tailored to what we needed.

Responsive to questions within a reasonable timeframe.  Offers constructive experience-based guidance intended to aid the student and increase individual learning.  Lectures are interesting, thought-stimulating and practical; a mix of presentation and application of concepts via mini-breakouts.  Applies story-telling as an effective learning aid.

Dr. Blair has provided thought-provoking in-person lectures on storytelling and resilience. She coached me on ways I can minimize stress before presenting and focus on my message. The end result was a successful presentation because of her coaching! I would jump at the opportunity to attend any course where Dr. Madelyn Blair teaches!

I love Dr. Blairs powerful message about three leadership qualities: insatiable curiosity, self aware and deep knowledge. She has helped me become a better knowledge professional and her work has been eye opening. Anyone would be lucky to have the opportunity to work with someone who is as passionate and wise as Dr. Blair. She is simply amazing!

Dr. Blair is a fantastic instructor. She excels at effectively communicating the course content, including breaking down and simplifying concepts. Additionally, she really cares about her students. I asked for a one on one meeting to discuss the course and my progress within the course, and she was very receptive, providing constructive feedback an

I've taken a few classes with Pat and they're really what you make of them. She gives the framework for you to take off with the material and produce work or you can also just sit back and blow it off, but you'll be bored beyond belief. She gives great lesson ideas but beware of any class with trips or too much media-hella disorganizedincohesive.

Zumhagen, like most TC faculty, play the charade of the academic but fail to conduct classes that are any more challenging than what you would find at your typical community college. Her lame air of theatricality would only convince the most naive of students.
The BEST. Amazingly fair, interesting, gives great assignments, cares about teaching, models wonderful teaching strategies in the classroom. A real star. Recommend highly.
Brilliant fun interesting. The best teacher I have had at Columbia by far.
Pat Zumhagen is a fabulous professor.  She's a gifted and creative teacher, always clear and very knowledgable and supportive.  I highly recommend her courses.
An absolutely amazing lady.  There's not much else that can be said.  I'm sure she'll be fabulous at Columbia.

He was amazing in the classroom, very dynamic and engaging. Once we moved online (due to covid), a little less theatrical, and our class was not as engaged. Fairly light class, two short papers. I enjoyed the course overall and would recommend if you are looking for a fun class to complement core requirements.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Respected--Graded by few things

comment: Dr. Langer is personable, knowledgeable, and engaging. While a lot of his material is more experiential and anecdotal than strict reading, it comes from a career of success in a variety of fields. He can be a bit rigid on certain concepts, but his class is energetic and enjoyable from start to finish.

Hard to believe it's been almost 10 years since I had him at Columbia. He was the face of the Technology Management program. I almost needed a chiropractor carrying around the 6 or so books he required but other than that I highly recommend him. I found him to be engaging, enthusiastic and knowledgeable. He poured his heart into the program.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment: Art was joke, no one took his class seriously. He was offensive to students and unprepared for class. Not an effective instructor, unhelpful feedback and unclear course assignments. Knowledgeable as if frequently watches shark tank.
Excellent professor.  Demanding but fair.

Langer is a visionary, who is the "godfather" of the Columbia University Technology Management program.  He teaches the 1st executive seminar, product realization, and the introductory Technology in a Business Environment.  He prepares middle management bound IT to succeed with and become senior execs, many of whom mentor in the program.
Great teacher and professional. He shares his experience and expertise as much as possible for the students to learn. You take away so much from his class. Also great sense of humor.

Safety is indeed one of the important areas in construction, but can be boring to learn, however, i feel Joseph's unique teaching methodology has made it very interesting for students to learn this subject. I would appreciate the efforts that professor makes in arranging guest lectures of various industry experts. I would highly recommend him.
rating_tags: Amazing lectures --Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback

comment: Professor Schwed is an awesome teacher. He cares about what his students take away from each class. As a result he constantly updates his presentations with later information and makes himself available to meet before or after class. I highly recommend taking his safety course if you get the chance.

What stands out about professor Schwed is how passionate he is about the subject matter he teaches. That is very clear through his lectures and the effort he takes to ensure his students walk away with a thorough understanding of safety. He truly cares about transferring his experience and knowledge to his students.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Clear grading criteria

comment: Best Professor Ever in my life.

Joe taught construction safety in a way that wasnt utterly boring to endure! It also helps that everything he discussed was directly applicable to my career. He is a very fair grader and willing to offer guidance for real-world scenarios you may encounter. I really enjoyed the class.
rating_tags: Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.--Would take again

comment: makes simple concepts confusing. The class is a mandatory class and if it was not many people not to take his class. Hes just shouting andis ESL no one can understand his  saying

I passed his course owing to the math tutor. His lectures were unhelpful. I would never take a math course with Gerratana if I had to. His homework is very heavy and even though you can use the lecture notes for your exam they will not help you to get A.

Great professor but somewhat difficult to follow his thought process (because he is that brilliant). The class is a tough one so be prepared to work, work, work. He is very easy to approach and really wants his students to do well so that's a plus!

He is absolutely EXCELLENT. There is no better teacher. It shows that he cares about your learning, he plans very throughly what and HOW he is going to say. Explains everything with passion and truly wants you to learn.And he is very intelligent and FUNNY!
I liked his class generally. A little bit hard but he is very enthusiastic person. He can teach..
very hard teacher, not enough clarity, and eplanations

If you're a good writer and you want to become a great one, take Bennet. You will never get track changes. You will have to read aloud and have oral macro edits. Write down all his aphorisms. Remember these: Make it interesting (pitches included), no cliches EVER, make your scenes into a movie, a good idea is 90% of the work & above all write well.

John is great. Yes, you will never get anything back line edited from him, but when you read out loud in class, he gives you the edits that are most important. His value is in the ear he has as a longtime editor - he know what works and what doesn't just by listening to your text. His overall wisdoms about writing and life are very valuable too.

Oh my god, what are you people talking about. You should write down every damn thing he says because he is WISE. People who complain about him are dolts who just want to get ahead and don't understand instruction that doesn't come in the form of line editing. Man.
Funny and entertaining.  But he keeps telling us not to be magazine writers, so why are we even bothering?

John may not do line edits, but he also doesn't leave you feeling like an idiot. He works to get to know each student by arranging a lunch with each of us. Taking a class with John allows a j-school student to go outside the boundaries. He's amazing, he's honest and he allows a student to feel proud about their work while criticizing all the while.

Bennet works at the New Yorker.  He tells good stories but he makes students read their work out loud....not fun.  He also rarely gives detailed line edits to stories and is generally detached.  He didn't get to know me at all.
I am sure she has done amazing things in her career but she does NOT need to teach any longer.

This professor was miserable.  Her classes were incredibly boring, class discussion was limited to about two people commenting on their personal experiences with advocacy.  Her voice was barely audible.  Further, her assignments were vague and she was somewhat condescending when answering questions about them.
Worst. Teacher. Ever.
She is a very supportive professor and wants the students to do well and learn a lot.  Low pressure.  Great environment.  Learned a lot.
Cool course.  Fairly easy.  Nice prof.  Very intellegent and enthusiastic.  I don't know why someone wouldn't sign up to study with her.

McGowan literally wrote the book on child welfare.  She is also the chair of the PhD program. If you want to get the most out of your CUSSW experience, take her class. She is a giant in her field, but is totally down to earth and quite nice.  She wants you to succeed. Other profs are more "slick", but McGowan is a wealth of knowledge & experience.

He introduced me to certain poetry, music, and literature  that became my favorites. No one ever flattered my poems as well as he--with sensitivity, depth, and enthusiasm. His lectures dissolved me in laughter--he's so witty.  I took every classs with him I could.  Sure, he's used to being the smartest person in the room: It's usually true.
dull dull dull.  astoundingly unhelpful and unkind.
No Comments
the difficulty is putting up with the big head that houses an incredibly narrow mind.

Great teacher A++
SUPER GOOD TEACHER!
THE BEST TEACHER. EVER
Best teacher. ever.
Super teacher, like her a lot!
Writes and speaks too fast.
Sara cares so much about students. It's exceptional and really made my SIPA experience. I fully recommend her classes and loved the academic freedom she gave us.

I really wanted to like prof Tjossem, but as others have alluded to, she is close minded and fails to support students equally. She has clear favorites. If you disagree with her worldview, she will dismiss you. She rambles. 95% of students in our lecture were multitasking thanks to her approach.

Favorite Professor I've had thus far as a graduate student here at Columbia. Passionate about the subject, highly knowledgeable, and invested in her students' success, she stands apart from other professors.

I would describe Sara with one word caustic. She seems all warm and emotive during lecture but if you offer up an idea which doesn't sync with her small worldview she will ignore you forever. Totally small minded.

Professor Tjossem is one of those rare professors that gets you excited about the subject. She has a deep understanding and passion for agriculture and sustainability, and it shows in her lectures. She speaks technically sometimes, but it's challenging and sparks tons of interest. Highly recommended!

Lecturer in the Environmental Science and Policy MPA program at SIPA. Dr. Tjossem teaches Environmental Policy, except "teach" might be too generous a verb. She rambles, fails to connect or even finish most points and lacks cohesiveness in her lectures. It is sad that this is our env. policy class for an MPA program. I'd like better!

There were errors in her powerpoint notes and notes written on the board. I agree with her other students here: It will be hard to see how anyone can learn from her lectures. Her lecture on EdX is an unflattering representation of Columbia University.
crazy exams, crazy homeworks, bad grade, no curve at all.
Crazy midterm and final. Only herself can understand the questions on the exam.
The lectures and homework are confusing.

She is helpful and is ready to explain all over again. Office hours are not wasted by anyone. However this course does more of a overview than explaining matter in depth. Midterms and Exams are crazy tough. Only 1/3 of class gets A, which is departmental policy. This course requires very high research and practice on R. Do NOt take hw lightly.

Professor DeRosa is the simply the best professor I ever had! I agree with everyone on here. Crystal clear communicator, always there when you need help, and very intriguing. I wish I could take him again.

Who would have ever thought higher level math could be so interesting and fun. Seriously, Professor DeRosa just makes everything so intriguing and enjoyable, and at the same time makes the subject matter crystal clear. It feels more like we were being entertained causing us to being fully engaged while all the time we were learning. EXCELLENT!!!!!!

Wow, all I could say is that he was the best professor I ever had. I wish more professors could teach like him, and at the same time have the presence he has when he teaches. Always there when we need him, and I learned so much as he makes the material so easy to understand. Bravo!
The best Professor I have ever experienced. He is so clear in his instruction. I wish every Professor was like him. Great with the students, and always there if you need him after class. AMAZING!

The best math professor ever. He is really clear on teaching mathematics which is rare at this level, and he is also very helpful outside the classroom. I heard somewhere that he might have moved back to working on Wall Street, but if he is still here I highly recommend. Oh and he is kind of an italian hottie.

I took an Intro to C Programming class with Sonny as a Columbia High School Summer Program. The experience was amazing. I went into the class with almost no coding experience, and he was able to turn me into a confident amateur coder. Sonny taught us the fundamentals in a clear and concise fashion. He is by far the best teacher that I've ever had.

I had Songqiao Li "Sonny" over the summer during the Columbia University summer program. He was a great professor who made class interesting everyday. Sonny encouraged group work, and was always available to answer questions or clear doubts. I really enjoyed Sonny's class and would highly recommend him to anyone interested in CS.
Sonny is a really good teacher. He always prepares for the class and gives clear explanation on new topics which is really helpful for me.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Amazing lectures

comment: An excellent professor who makes a real effort to teach.
i wrote 20+ programs in 3 weeks :)

Hassan was an excellent Professor. He was ideal for this class, as he was able to tutor me not just on a theoretical level, but also using his expertise as a Career Mastermind. I highly recommend that Hassan teach other classes. We need Professors that truly care, and are not apathetic (I have found that some are). Thank you Hassan!!

Brilliant Professor! One of the last pieces of advice (of many) he gave me before graduating was that your greatest asset is your current job, as you will be using it as a bridge job for the next job and it will help market you (along with references you align); protect it, leverage it, maximize it! He rocks! He should teach more classes!!!!!!!!

Of all the professors I have taken at Columbia, he is the most fresh and innovative. What he says MAKES SENSE, and gives analogies that are really invaluable If I wouldn't have taken this class, I would have been lost, as my career track isn't that straightforward and he made it clear for me. He prepares you for the "future of meaningful work".

A must take professor at the Sch of Professional Studies. He teaches you about personal branding and positioning in your career, as well as playing well in the sandbox. That your current job is your biggest asset as it makes you more marketable and serves as a bridge job. Loved the course and him. They are lucky to have him!

He should be teaching leadership, one of my favorite professors of all time! Take his class! He motivated me to not second guess myself and add true meaning to my career/life vision. He shared a framework on how to align my purpose and I have never gotten that kind of career coaching before. No surprise he has so many thank you cards in his office!
Best teacher I've ever had. Changed my writing and my life for the better.

Fasano is the best. The seminar I took with him helped me with my writing and also introduced me to writers I was overlooking. I feel I'm writing better than I ever have (I'm a nontraditional student returning to education after some years away), and I definitely have Fasano to thank for that. Very inspiring.

I took one of Fasano's seminars, "The Crisis of the I," discussing selfhood in modern/postmodern/contemporary poetics. It was an amazing class. Fasano's also just a really nice person who will help you with your own writing if you ask. Really generous. I wish I'd taken his poetic meter and form class.

I took two classes with Fasano, including this one (poetic meter and form). He's not only a great teacher, but he's also really helpful during office hours. He helped me put together a whole portfolio of my own writing by the end of the semester. He really cares about both literature and his students, which is a great combo. I miss his classes.
Outstanding professor; very passionate about the subject matter (infectiously so).
She was very friendly, but I often got grades I didn't feel I deserved. She grades tough and is apparently mean to select students.

Incredible professor. It's a lot of work and the bar is set high, but you are given all the tools to succeed (unparalleled class materials and organization). Would take a class by her in a heartbeat. Also haven't met a more accessible professor at Columbia. Definitely go to OH -- super helpful
Gem of a professor! Tough class, but you learn a lot

TLDR: it's a high bar and you're given all the tools to succeed. Comprehensive lectures incorporating spiral review, practice problems representative of her tests, accessible for questions/extra help. Orgo is like visiting the Titanic, and this is the tried-and-true steel sub. Sure, composites are lighter, but then again they don't always work.

talha is an AMAZING professor. i took orgo 1 lecture with her and she explains orgo in super easy way. her tests are very fair and gives a lot of practice. u need to go to lecture because she usually doesnt post her notes but her lectures are super clear and easy to understand that i always found myself WANTING to go to her class. best prof i had!

comment: THE WORST PROFESSOR I HAVE EVER HAD, disrespectful to students and unhelpful

There are TONS of homework every week & the most boring lecture. You don't have to come to this class in person because you will not learn anything helpful. The most crucial part is that the final exam has so many questions that you will never finish! Remember, the final exam weighs 40% of your final grade & NO CURVE in this class.

He teaches R really fast. You wouldn't have enough time to take your notes,  If you didn't have experience in R, it's impossible for you to catch up. In week 4, it's already machine learning.  You need to spend a lot time to go through the reading, lectures notes before the class. Otherwise you will not able to understand what he's saying.

I burned my fingers last semester and could hardly type to finish the final exam. Prof. Shilane and my caring academic advisor Katie offered great help during that difficult period. Thank you so much professor!

He is the most responsible instructor that I have ever met. He goes above and beyond to help out and is very reasonable when it comes to grading. I have had his class for 2 semesters, and I have never met an instructor responds this fast to students' email all the time. Super grateful to have him as my instructor amid the pandemic.
She was very kind. There were few assignments. And she was an easy grader.

Rating the program eval class: She's very convoluted. I had high hopes because she actually had some nice reviews here. My experience has been a disappointing one. She seems nice enough though and gives good feedback/critique on hw, so that's her saving grace. I wouldn't take a research related course with her again..perhaps she's better for HBSE?
HBSE is a course in stating the obvious.  It must be for people that grew up in a bubble.  Eri did a great job with the lame material.  Also, she is supportive and responds to student emails.

I think she is a great professor.  She did really well considering the material she was given to teach us was superficial and at the level of freshman undergrad survey course.  I enjoyed working with her and it pisses me off that she gets blamed for crappy cirriculum,  Actually, all of the HBSe teachers get flack for this crappy ass course.
She is energetic but not especially nice when push comes to shove. The inherently superficial material in the HBSE curriculum was in no way enhanced by her superficial handling of it!

Very nice and wholesome professor. His class was on the slower side but he is able to explain things clearly. Sometime's he'll run into bugs and debug code live in class and get stuck but honestly it happens to the best of professors. Assignments are on the harder side and are consuming. Exams are okay but you'll definitely need to put work in.

Do NOT take Game Theory with this guy. It is absolutely the WORST class I have ever taken in my life. The class starts off easy, slowly progresses in difficulty and then all of a sudden you're taking the hardest class you have ever taken in your life. AWFUL.

comment: Great professor, very kind and empathetic toward his students, and I loved his Game Theory course. However, he assigns A LOT of homework and it is very frequent. I think there were very few days over the course of the entire semester that I was not working on a Game Theory problem set.
Must take his class

Professor Ortega is absolutely incredible! They focus on trauma informed care which is right up my ally and we learned SO MUCH in our 14 weeks of class. You SHOULD NOT get your MSW from Columbia without taking a class with Professor Ortega, for REAL!

Prof Ortega is amazing. She is well-informed, well-intentioned and instructs with care and positive intentions. I think she is a rockstar and should teach HBSE-I forever. I walked away from the course with knowledge that will guide me in life and in my career.

Wonderful professor. Genuinely cares about understanding human behavior in varied contexts. LOVE her teaching style, creative, genuine caring. Diverse and relevant topics. Fully engaged. NEVER BORED. As a non-traditional student in my 50's, I am impressed with her vast knowledge. Best professor. Don't leave Columbia and not experience her class.

Professor Ortega is hands-down one of the best professors I have ever had in my life. She is knowledgable, caring, and helpful. She treats you like an adult and expects you to know your material and reading. She challenges your thinking. I absolutely recommend taking a class with her if you can. You will not regret it.
SHE IS AMAZING. YOU WILL LEARN AND TAKE AWAY SO MUCH FROM THIS CLASS. ASSIGNMENTS ARE ENLIGHTENING AND EASY TO FINISH.

His enthusiasm, engagement, effervescence and philosophical energy kept me reading all his assignments, biting my nails at each question, shattered at every revelation regarding subjects ranging from history to mere life. And yet he was so clear with even the most impossible. Rarely can one do that with names like Benjamin, Derrida and Heidegger.

Dr. mult. Nichanian is an experience of his own: Never have I met a teacher who's so wonderfully engaged, both with his subject(s) and his students. To know him is to learn from him, what better can one say of a teacher? Why Columbia has a man like him allowed to leave I'll never, never understand: It's a shame for this university!
took his classes a number of years ago, and they are still among the best classes i've taken. Nichanian is great, very intelligent, thought-provoking and really nice to his students.
Of my four years at Columbia and four years at Harvard, Prof. Nichanian remains the most dedicated, warm, and inspiring teachers that I have studied with.

An exceptional scholar, a wonderful human being. Prof. Nichanian is one of the few professors that I know who has the ability to bring together students from all disciplines, languages, backgrounds. Columbia needs to bring him back, as he is a much needed voice for today's scholarship in Armenian

Dr. Harris is definitely knowledgable but he covers far too much information for it to be possible to learn it all. I took this out of interest but I found myself frustrated almost every lecture. By far the best class while I was at Columbia. Dr. Harris is amazingly knowledgeable and skilled at lecturing, the materials for the class were great (like the other rater said--primary sources! but also a good text). I never missed a single lecture and I never laughed so hard as in his class. His humor's a testament to his intelligence. ROME!!!
he's knowledgeable and interesting to listen to.  he's an excellent teacher.

As a history teacher today, I thanbk Dr. Harris for teaching history as it should be; with analysis of primary sources, disussions centered around reliability, interpretations and validity of historical evidence.  His teaching did not leave anyone behind.
the best guy to go to if you want to learn the history of Rome

Excellent professor, difficult problem sets became manageable in time for tests and test questions are only slightly more difficult than in class problem sets. Keep up though and go to office hours if you have difficulties

Lectures were so boring and tests were hard - not a fun professor. Took multiple classes with her and each time the assignments became more lengthy.

lectures are boring and confusing. He makes kindergarten level stats unnecessarily elusive. Grading process does not make sense. boring, sometimes you don't even hear what he is saying. the course is taught by TA's mostly. material that he gives is not structured and he changes the deadlines as he wants to. very confusing homework.

Doru was my favorite Professor at SIPA. He truly cares about his students and their ability to learn the material. He has a top notch teaching team and is highly organized. Clearly outlines material for the exams

Best math professor I've ever had. I hope to take him again and I liked how he spoke about math related medical fields including computational neuroscience. unpleasant, goes off on tangents too frequently

His lectures always blow my mind, as he is incredibly woke/real/Zen/etc. He leaves you thinking about social/racial issues in a different light and has an incredible wealth of knowledge. However, if you need clear structure or a Prof who responds to emails, don't take James. He believes in independent crit thinking, so there is NO structure. Easy A

Awesome professor!!! Learned so much in this class. Read the assigned reading and you'll get the most out of class and not sound stupid when you participate.

She is enthusiastic, engaging, beyond knowledgeable, and highly experienced in DBT, which makes learning from her feel like a gift. She is attentive to student needs and gives fantastic feedback. To top it off, she's down-to-earth, fun, and hilarious! The BEST!

At first, Prof. Pratt's class seemed to be easy-going. But it was my misconception. After midterm, he required us to read a lot of things and memorize them. More seriously, just a few got A because of final exam; it was super hard.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Gerri is an absolutely incredible prof. She is so knowledgeable about clinical practice. Her classes are so engaging and interactive, and she's great at facilitating student discussion. She clearly cares so deeply for her students (and clients). Highly recommend!
I was not sure how to science, But with Dr. Landheer's guidance, Where I used to be just a poet, Watch out Samuel Abraham Goudsmit. Now, I'm just as good as physics as I am poetry.

Professor Mu is definitely one of the best professor I've ever met. He truly knows what he teaches, thus can answer any question during the lecture. Homeworks are well organized so if you follow them you can easily keep up with the materials. Also he is really kind, gentle and nice to his students. He will not hesitate to give you good advices
A great teacher...he really knows how to communicate.
A really dedicated instructor who is committed to her profession and her students
I did not find Professor Hedrick an effective teacher on IPP. Her lectures and assignments were unclear.
One of my favorite professors at Columbia. Reinforcement Learning was a good class, and she takes her time to derive and explain things clearly.
Decent lectures, but completely inaccessible outside of class. Does not share his grading scale with the class. Does not care about students at all.

Prof. Simunovic is hot. We learned thermodynamics from him and I literally couldn't focus for the first three classes.  I've got it under control now, we will see what my grade ends up as, but it doesn't matter if I fail it. I'll happily take it again.

This course was a lot more work than I expected, mainly due to the weekly homeworks.  If you are into reverse engineering and assembly code, this class will be perfect for you.  The professor seems like a genuinely nice guy, but unfortunately the topic really just wasn't my niche so it was quite difficult and time consuming for me.
Very good professor. Intense class, lots of homework, but good teacher. Will take again
Professor Salter made one of my most difficult subjects much less miserable

I had Professor Weisgrau for a summer session at Columbia, and she was amazing. The lectures can be long but Prof breaks it down with 10-15 minutes breaks and has Q&As almost class. There can be lots of readings: her book and multiple ethnographies. The study guide is really helpful and includes everything on the exam. Wonderful summer expierence.
rating_tags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Amazing lectures

comment: Jessica was an absentee professor with no regard for her students. She cancelled multiple investigative techniques classes and never even submitted our final grades. Her lack of effort and follow through was shameful.

His sarcasm was like the hallmark of his personality and it was annoying because it excessive. He always had to make sassy comments that, at times, were just unnecessary and unprofessional. Poor lecturer too so none of the classes felt worth the $ and time to be honest. I benefitted more from Youtube videos. Not a super hard class though.

Dr. BB is a good professor. She really care about students, really care about what they learn from the class. By taking her class, you not only learn stuffs but also make a friend with her. She is enthusiastic every class, you won't get bored. I am Gonna miss her class.

Overall I taught myself using the materials and the lecture wasn't helpful other than very generic content such as a resume critique with generalized feedback you might receive from Career Services. Some funny stereotypes of bad Professors exist with her lots of self-promotion. Did not encourage discussion or create the right class environment.

Dr. Ferguson was great - hilarious lectures, assignments & take home tests where you can copy-paste answers from the slides to success, and extremely useful subject matter (databases and how they work). He also mocks stupid questions in real time (don't worry - if you actually pay attention and have real questions, he helps).

Professor continuously sought to alienate students in different ways, whether that be by supporting and uplifting some or degrading others. She has many good ideas and lectures but these were overshadowed by her continuous unprofessionalism. I do not suggest taking her.

This professor is extremely unprofessional. She pointed out and named two students whom she felt "supported by" and was extremely rude and dismissive to the students who respectfully asked for clarification throughout the semester  . More than half of the class went to administration to complain that she was grading with bias.

Professor Boston goes through community guidelines every week and she states "feelings are not facts" yet she brought her personal feelings into the class. Sent the class an email stating that students should start writing like "Columbian students" and that she is surprised many students got into Columbia with the way the assignments are written.

Professor Boston challenged me to lean into discomfort and encouraged me to think beyond what my environment has lead me to believe thus far.  She is REAL with her students and for that reason a lot of people really struggle in her course.  Very different than any other course experience, but such a gift!

Professor Boston is an amazing professor, I would recommend that everyone take her at least once if they get the chance. She is interactive with her students and creates a classroom enviornment that is a safe and brave space for all who enter. She is challenging and gives great feedback, you will leave her class with a new perspective on life.

I am in my second semester as an engineering student here at Columbia- taking this course has completely solidified my desire to be an engineer. Professor McIlvain is knowledgeable and engaging- she makes the material easily digestible and memorable through unique lab activities. Great to have a fellow woman as a teacher- very encouraging.

I would recommend taking her for Motivational Interviewing. Professor Azzarelli makes the sessions very interesting, and she gives time to practice the skills in break-out rooms. There is a required log each week for homework, but it is easy to complete. This course has no credit, but you are required to get a P in the course.
rating_tags: Amazing lectures --Clear grading criteria--Graded by few things

comment: Professor Nair is a great professor. I would recommend taking him for social welfare policy. The course requires you to complete 11 discussion posts and a group paper split into four parts. You will also need to complete a presentation on one of the assigned readings or videos throughout the semester, but there is nothing to fear.

She is a real gem in the German Department of the University. I would absolutely recommend all of her courses (I have taken 3 in total). She is insightful, a great lecturer and really allows every student no matter their level of German to be able to participate. You can take her whether you're fluent or still learning. Essays in english, one in GE
She is super nice and knows her field!
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback

comment: I liked Professor Kostina and her class. It gave a good understanding of how Russian media has changed over the last thirty years since the USSR ended. There was a lot to cover, but her approach was organized and balanced. The class included weekly reading responses, a mid-term paper, and a final paper.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Gives good feedback--Graded by few things

comment: Prof Kostina is kind, supportive, and well-organized. The lectures and discussions are structured and engaging. Watching Russian documentaries and movies was a great way to experience a culture I hadn't encountered before. She grades fairly and provides detailed feedback on the first draft of the final paper.
rating_tags: Participation matters--Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback

comment: A wonderful professor who is friendly, approachable, and flexible. She strikes a great balance between lectures and class discussions.Classroom environment is low-pressure and allows for different ideas and perspectives. Her structured and organized approach, along with the variety of readings and media genres, is a huge plus.
rating_tags: Participation matters--Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback

comment: 3rd year Korean Course.  Heavy work load, but professor is highly organized and there are no surprises.  fast paced.  Schulz is a leading expert in the teaching of Korean Language.
great guy... couldnt have taught the class better myself...
TOTAL ****. AVOID.

I am an international student, and I've enjoyed taking Erik's class. Unlike other professors in Columbia who teach ESL writing/English, and read word for word from the textbook like some factory robots, Erik provides new practical approach to acing exams and writing projects  (weekly interactive writing workshops, analysisofcontemp literary works)
No Comments

Dr Knapp obviously knows the material. But when it comes to teaching his notes aren't at all clear. Plus if you go to his office hours for questions half of the time he isn't even there. But when he is in his office he is unpatient and seems to want you out ASAP.
Epistemology was fantastic.  Very focused and eye-opening.

I have mixed feelings about Prof Chen. She is very kind and sweet, but I did not connect with her teaching style. The lectures are very dry. She does try to incorporate other things like group work and videos, but they still don't seem to be that engaging.

I'll start this by saying that policy is a difficult subject to teach. That being said she focused more on our writing than the content we were learning. I get why, but I really wanted to grasp more concepts and ideas in class, which I didn't feel like I did. She was often confusing and confused about our assignments and not that helpful.
A very knowledgeable Professor in his field. He teaches about the HIV/AIDS epidemiology with thousand of references not only from journals/research, but also from movies, arts etc. He is amazing!!

Script Analysis: though didn't spend a lot of time on scripts.  Mostly film analysis and breaking down how the story works.  Lots of Hero's Journey stuff, but alternative structures as well.  Good teacher I wish more were like him.   Treats us like adults.  Overall a great class experience in more ways than one.

Hard to believe someone from a country that went 2 years without a government would be hired at a policy school, but Prof Coolen teaches with the passion of a master waffle-maker, the wry wit of a sarcastic chocolatier, and the adventurous spirit of Tintin. A stylish dresser, he regales the class with his tales of working in the trenches of the UN.

That this class was billed as a "seminar" is false. She dominated the discussions speaking over 75% of the time, and only allowed for discussion insofar as she agreed with what was being said. Her grading style was the same. She only liked your work if she agreed with it, rather than if it was argued well. Very frustrating.
rating_tags: Tough Grader--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: She never gives you a good grade. Most students get B+ or A-, even though A is very normal for graduate school. She is very very tough on grading. You can learn a lot from her. If you want to get a good grade, just do not take her class. For the project delivery, she wants you to follow her idea extremely. Your creative seems meaningless.
Paul gives good francais!
Very hot, but once she starts opening her mouth you just want to leave. Very hard but at least she knows what she's doing. Barely gives out A's so don't expect one.

One of the best professors I've ever had. SW students who don't get the pleasure of taking her class are truly missing out. Always looked forward to her lectures. Fair grader. Loved the emphasis on research ethics.
PORT 1220 It was great!
Cs. Theory
Lectures are pretty detailed and thorough.
Awesome teacher

Dr. Ramirez had an insane knowledge of Latina/o Theatre. Took the course through the Center for Study of Ethnicity during my senior year. I have not seen him teaching any other classes. Hope he is still at Columbia. Important topic that needs to be explored. Bravo!
She's good if you really walked into class knowing NOTHING. Don't show up unless you've prepped for class, or she'll kick you out.
Professor Sanchez is awesome! I'm excited that he started teaching this class. The tests were difficult but the lectures are on topic and quite interesting. I'm an Econ major and I found it great.

This course was pretty easy. We spent way too much time on professor Branas research and not much else. The epi methods used were very basic; i didnt learn much in this course that i couldnt have learned from reading his coauthored journal papers.

Michelle is by far one of the most caring professors I have had at Columbia. If you engage she will always ensure that you are being supported in all the right ways to advance your knowledge. Would definitely recommend!

Mr. Armstrong was a great instructor! We covered a TON of ground in a short amount of time but he explained everything super clearly and made things fun. He also gave excellent feedback on the final paper that helped improve my writing. And he's super cute so...

Really sweet professor who wants to help her students learn and succeed long after grad school. Assignments were clear and not terribly difficult. She's always willing to answer any/all questions during class. The only downside is that sometimes, this takes away from learning about course material but it *is* a 3 hour class so it's understandable.

Ben is an absolutely fantastic professor which I would recommend to everyone. The course is very educational. Ben is very knowledgeable in the field, a terrific lecturer, funny, and friendly. He brings so much energy and enthusiasm to class that it's simply very entertaining. Highly recommend to anyone in the Applied Analytics program.
Great Professor!!!
Good

He definitely knows his stuff but he uses academic jargon that's really lofty and hard to understand. Sometimes he doesn't understand the arguments students are trying to make and doesn't really listen to them, his mind is pretty much already made up and he has no intention of changing it.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Graded by few things--Tough grader

comment: Dr. Terrana is amazing professor! I wish she was teaching SWK-501. She is very knowledgable. We only had one small paper to do 2-3 pages and we had to do an annotated bibliography. We had readings every week and we had discussions on Moodle. She is always available for help. She wants us to improve and do well. She truly cares about her students.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Gives good feedback

comment: Professor Tai puts a lot of focus on his lectures, which are very interesting and often inspirational. He doesn't give out a free A but is very fair as long as you have critical thinking skills. His class provides a great foundation if you want to be majored in Art History.
Gives Bad feedback and Vague instructions with unclear grading criteria. Try not to take his sustainability management class. Though, relatively light workload but with a bad grade :(

Dr. O was an okay teacher for Foundations of SW Practice. She talks a lot in person anecdotes which are sometimes helpful and sometimes not. Get ready to read. Not very tech savy. Friendly but not warm.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Lots of homework

comment: He is absolutely terrible. The worst teacher I have ever had.

Poorly crafted lectures. Exams have no correlation with the homework assignments or lectures and are graded harshly.  Refused to comment on the curve for the course after being asked directly. This was unfortunately a required course, would not recommend for any electives either.

While Prof de Abreu is very knowledgeable on the subject matter, I feel that this course is extremely disorganized and not well-planned, maybe because she also missed many classes this semester. The readings she chose were not inspiring and the classes were quite boring. Prof de Abreu is probably better at research than she is at teaching.

Poorly organized deadlines. She and the TA sent an email and WhatsApp message during Thanksgiving Vacation (Wednesday through Sunday). Message on Saturday said to complete work on the model by Sunday, and email on Friday said to send drawings by Monday. Inflicting short notice deadlines on us during Thanksgiving Break is disrespectful to students.

As far as GSAPP professors go, she's pretty good. Large introduction class which is then supplemented by sections led by doctoral students. She was flexible with the assignments which was thoughtful. Material was engaging and diverse.
only do coding for himself, not for students, students cannot catch the pace of the class if don't have the foundation

Professor Josz's teaching level is as moderate as his hair. The class is average level with some average TAs. Do not recommend unless you are pretty confident with your quantitative skills. It is indeed ashamed that Columbia does not put too much efforts on this core curriculum in the department.
rating_tags: Lecture heavy--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment:
TLDR: One of the best professors, certainly *the* best teacher at Columbia. 
(1) lecture+problem-solving format of class time leads to actual learning+retention(+fun) 
(2) teaches to all parts of class 
(3) legendary lecture notes 
(4) fair tests w. clear expectations
(5) kind person.

So good you'd think he was the Organic Chemistry Tutor.

How can someone cram a marketing class with so many meaningless, trivial, time-wasting tasks just in one semester? And then when grading don't say why were the points deducted and what's the criteria? (*^_^*) If you will choose this class, good luck to you (*^_^*)

Professor Rondina is very engaging and knowledgeable. She balances lectures with interactive activities well. I took her online (Adobe Connect) class & she was the only professor out of all my classes who engaged with the chat throughout the course. She was also the only one who held office hours regularly and was easy to reach.

This professor talks a lot in the lecture but barely any of the lecture is related to work He is strict about attendance and arriving on time and uses it for the grade even though he was late quite a few times. Avoid because if you take his class you will be confused about what is expected but he grades as if you are already skilled in the subject.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Participation matters--Graded by few things

comment: This was the worst class ever. If you get Harrison for Capstone, drop it. There is no clear grading criteria. She does not follow the rubric. You are working for her, not your assigned company. You learn how to deal with difficult people, not actually how to consult for a company, let alone any analytics.

RUN. The appearance does not reflect reality. Deliberately & intentionally transforms a simple subject into a complex and confusing one. Undoubtedly, this is an area that should be avoided at all costs. A course that is taught by just one professor with no wiggle room and does not offer other realistic alternatives is truly not worth your effort
Lectures are generally stuffed but contain lots of information. But he has the toughest grader ever. Lots of points were deducted from meaningless stuff...

Professor Green is great. I would recommend taking her Human Behavior in the Social Environment course. However, you need to know that the final paper assignment determines 60% of your grade, so please stay focused in class so you do not become lost. Otherwise, the rest of the small assignments are easy to complete.
rating_tags: Tough grader--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment: 15% Coursework postings each week. Attendance is 0%, and Active participation in discussion is 20%, which means you need to arrive and talk in class every time (points off if you don't talk in any class).5pages mid-semester paper is 25%, and 10pages final paper is 40%. The average grade is B for this pro and A- for another professor (Same class).
Heavy workload with harsh grading. No extra credit. Boring reading materials.

I don't have any critical comments on the course content; the only thing I know is he is a tough grader. Everything is okay except the grade, so if you want to learn something about early China and don't care about your grade, pick his class. BTW, try not to attack or doubt his arguments in class; he tends to punish dissent by lowering grades.

Cheated on me by giving me a really good grade for the midterm paper, and a really bad grade for the final (For his evaluation). Lots of long, boring readings with his wired tone is a disaster. I would say Li Feng is a mean guy and a harsh grader. Giving 50% fair grade and 50% unfair is a great strategy that doesn't let everybody turn against him.

Don't take his class if you care about your grade. The worst professor I have ever met. Can't even speak English properly but is stern to his students. I got 2 A- for my papers but a D for my participation even though I attended on time all semester (I just didn't talk too much). I even gave him an excellent for the official course evaluation.

While Mr. Othman's course is highly praised, I personally struggled to fully enjoy it due to my ADHD. The lectures were rich with content, but the fast-paced discussions and extensive readings were challenging for me to keep up with. While the course wasn't an easy experience for me, I appreciated his effort to ensure every student could succeed

Mr Othman is a gem! His passion for Computer Science is contagious, and he makes complex topics feel approachable. Always available to help, he inspires us to think critically and innovate. Truly a mentor!
rating_tags: Amazing lectures --Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback
